{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608634/1957102101/0575.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING OTAR. Washington,\nMONDAY, OCTOaCB SI. ISSV\nA-20\nT Business\nW&L Sales Set Record\nAnd Earnings Increase\nBy DONALD B. HADLEY\nWoodward A Lothrop had record ulea of nearly s6l million\nand a alight Increase In profits In the fiscal year ended August\n3. stockholders learned at the annual meeting today.\nThe annual report presented by Board Chairman John Tys\naowski and President Andrew Parker listed net Income of\n61.978.171, compared with 11.874.258 In the previous year.\nIt amounted to 86.28 a share,\ncompared with $6.26 a share In\nthe previous year. It was 3.3\nper cent of sales, compared with\n3.6 per cent In the preceding\nperiod.\nRecord sales for the 51-week\nperiod ended August 3 wen\n10.83 per cent above $64,876,471\nin the preceding 52-week year,\nand the report commented that\na comparison for 62 weeks In\nboth years would leave a sales\ngain of 8.22 per cent.\nThey pointed out that for\nthe 63-week year, the Federal\nReserve figures show a sales In\ncrease of only 1.5 per cent for\nall major department stores In\nthis area, and added that some\nof the above-average increase\nas due to opening of the new\nSeven Corners store.\nHowever. Federal Reserve\nfigures indicate the downtown\nstore sales were about 2.3 per\ncent better than the downtown\naverage, the report said.\nBalance sheet for the year's\nend showed book value of the\ncommon stock was $58.48 a\n'share, compared with $67.02 a\nyear earlier.\nTyssowski Changes. Jobs,\nFig gins Added to Board\nMr. Tyssowski. who presided\nat today's Meeting, surprised\nstockholders by announcing his\nresignation as board chairman\nand abolition of that position.\nHowever, he was re-elected a\ndirector with other members of\nthe board and was named\nchairman of tl\\e board\u2019s Execu\ntive Committee to succeed\nLloyd B. Wilson, who has re\ntired from that position. Mr.\nWilson was re-elected as a\ndirector.\nWeston P. Plugins, vice pres\nident of personnel and opera\ntions. was elected a director to\nfill a board vacancy left by the\ndeath of Charles H Tompkins.\nAt the organizational board\nmeeting after the stockholders'\nsession. Ludwig J. Amtmann\nwas promoted from assistant\nvice president to vtoe president\nand general merchandise man\nager. and Walter R. Granger,\nassistant vice president, was\npromoted to vice president of\nbranch stores.\nBatie Indicates Need\nFar Mare Work Capital\nThe annual report pointed to\na decrease in the ratio of cur\nrent assets and liabilities to 2.51\nto 1 from 3.43 to l a year earlier\nand said this indicated a need\nfor additional capital. This\nneed has been met by a long\nterm open loan for $4 million.\nCurrent assets totaled $lB.-\n421.886 at the year end\nand current liabilities amounted\nto $7,725,266. A year earlier\ncurrent assets totaled $16,488.-\n821 and current liabilities\n$4,808,313.\nAs a result of capital ex\npenditures at the Seven Cor\nners store and to some extent\nto present expansion of the\nChevy Chase store, cash re\nquirements have risen substan\ntially. the report said.\n\u201cSales at the Seven Comers\nstore have been most gratifying\nand greatly exceed the first\nyear\u2019s planned figures.\u201d it con\ntinued. Results have con\nfirmed management\u2019s belief\nthat you grow bigger faster\nIn a well-planned shopping\n\u2022enter.\u201d\nConstruction which suited\nat the Chevy Chase store last\nFebruary will increase space 70\nper cent and is expected to\nbe completed early in the\nspring of 1958. All depart\nments will share in the in\ncreased space.\nElected Director in 1918,\nChairman Since 1948\nMr. Tyssowski has been a\nmember of the Woodward Sc\nLothrop board of directors since,\n1918 and was vice president\nfrom 1942 until July. 1948. when\nhe became board chairman.\nAs chairman he has been\nresponsible for formulating\nmajor store policies and direc\nted operations during a period\nin which major suburban units\nwere established, sales rose\nmore than 50 per cent and\nprofits soared 75 per cent.\nA mining engineering gradu\nate of the University of Cali\nfornia, Mr. Tyssoswkl had\nbroad experience with the C.\nH. Post, the American Foreign\nTrade Corp. and Bennett Day\nImporting Co., but returned to\nmining as president of the\nCopper Deoxidation Corp. from\n1928 to 1941 when he retired.\nHe now raises purebred Here\nford cattle on his farms in\nFauquier County. Va. He mar\nried Miss Catherine Woodward\nof Washington in 1915.\nMr. Wilson, formerly presi\ndent of the Chesapeake St Po\ntomac Telephone Co., has been\non the Woodward Sc Lothrop\nboard for eleven years and\nchairman of its executive com\nmittee for nine years.\nNew Director Joined Store\nOrganisation In 1949\nMr. Flggins, the new director,\nbecame associated with Wood\nward's in 1949 after holding\nsupervisory positions in the\npersonnel departments of Pratt\nSc Whitney Aircraft Corp. and\nStewart St Company of Balti\nmore.\nHe became personnel rela\ntions manager in May, 1950. and\npersonnel administration direc\ntor in October. 1981. He was\nelected divisional vice president\nIn charge of personnel and\ncustomer services In October,,\n1854, and was promoted to vice\nA n\n\u2019I\npresident of personnel, public\nI relations and customer services\nin October. 1956.\nI Mr. Amtmann joined Wood\nward 8k Lothrop in 1954 as dl\n-1 visional merchandise manager\nafter holding executive posl\nl tions willi leading stores In\nother cities He became as\nt sistant vice president and gen\n-1 eral merchandise manager In\n1 1956. He Is a graduate of Wes\nleyan University.\nr Mr. Granger joined the or\n-1 ganisation in 1931 and became\nbuyer of men\u2019s furnishings In\n1939. In 1947 he was named\ndivisional merchandise man-;\nager and became assistant vice\ns president and general mer- 1\nchandise manager in 1956. He\nassumed responsibility for\nbranch store operations last\ni July 1.\nIn addition to Mr. Tyssowski.\ni Mr Parker and Mr. Wilson, re\nelected directors Included:;\ni James W. Anderson. Lee D But\nler. Harry A. De\u00dfutts. Clar\nence Dodge. Jr., Nelson T.l\ni Hartson. Robert E. L. Johnson:\nJohn T. Koehler. A Lotherop\nLuttrell and Philip M. Talbott.\nI SEC Flies Coart Appeal\nI In Variable Annuity Case\n1 The Securities and Exchange\nCommission today appealed\nfrom an order of the United\nStates District Court In the\naction the agency brought\nagainst the Variable Annuity\nLife Insurance Co. and the\nEquity Annuity Life Insurance\nCo.\nThe court dismissed a com\nplaint filed by the commission\nwhich sought to enjoin the\ndefendants from violating the\nregistration provisions of the\nSecurities Act of 1933 and the\nInvestin'nt Company Act of\n1840 in connection with the\nsale of contracts described as\n\"variable annuity contracts.\u201d\nThe defendants contended\nthe contracts were insurance\npolicies specifically exempted\nfrom provisions of the Secur\nities Act of 1933 and that the\ndefendants themselves were\ninsurance companies and not\nsubject to provisions of the\nInvestment Company Act.\nThe SEC\u2019s decision to appeal\nwas applauded by Joseph E.\nWelch, president of the Na\ntional Association of Invest\nment Companies. He said the\ndecision \u201cshould be welcomed'\nfPf\nGo tb\u00ab 11\u2014^\n\u00a3tfnetCjo&\nosiw\nA/vJ 111 XiH Taj\nRESERVATIONS NOW AVAILAIIE B||U|hU3\nCAUt Santa ft Tic|zt Ojpcz, IIS Shnrzhem BU|. M\nWgihmgton 5, D. C., Ttltphnnt: DlMrxt 77984-5.\nH. N- Eccleiton, Du. Pass. A|t.\nIjjflj Hr\nI f\nhL J i\nI AWmr' m d\nJ\u00abt*a Tmmfcl AMnv Ptriw Url W!lm\nSi j.\nW. P. rictlai L. J. iaiMii W. B. Graagtr\nby all segments of the secur\nities industry.\u201d\nInflation DUemma Been\nThroughout Free World\nHow to stop inflation with\nout stopping the boom worries\nmonetary authorities and\nclouds the business outlook\nthroughout the free world, re\nported William R. Kuhns, edi\ntor of Banking magaaine today.\nIn the current November is\nsue. Mr. Kuhns declared: \u201cIt\n;1* an economic problem\nwrapped In politics, wrapped\nIn Mix and missile defense pol\nicies. wrapped in mass psy\nchology and human nature.\"\n\u201cThere are signs of success\nin solving it. and signs of fail\nure. but little evidence In his\nar that the feat has ever\nually been achieved- Without\nthe disciplinary power of gold. I\nall currencies are on a man-i\nj Med basis and subject to polit\nical pressure. Consequently. In\nsome countries the authorities\ndid not start to worry soon\nenough.\u201d he said.\nAula Dealers Are Urged\nNat to Exaggerate\nExaggerated claims of al\nleged savings which are fea\ntured in advertising and sell\ning by some automobile dealers\nwere called \u201cmisleading and de\nceptive\u201d this week by the Na\ntional Automobile Dealers As\nsociation. In an article in the\nassociation's weekly News-Let\nter members of NADA were\nasked to refrain from using\nsuch claims.\nNADA said that exaggerated\nand grotesque claims were in\nviolation of the association's\n\u2022Statement of Advertising\nFOREIGN EXCH'GE\nfollow 6 r*af'fclum* in\ndolltri. others la c*nls uiachuitd\nunless othrrwise noted):\nCanadian dollar in New Tort open\n\u201crtS* 111'\" P* r cent premium or\n103 781* O. 8. eonu. up 3 32\nf ope Oreol Britain (pound i.\nUP IS/SS; 30-ds\u00bb futurei.\nSi! 7/32. up 17/32. So-dor tuturei.\n17515/as up 13,33. 00-Oo\u00bb future*, i\nup *V\u00bb; Belelum (fr\u00bbncT\nI l.aaa. up uo.V: France (Trnno. .*3%: 1\nGermany (Weeteroi (deuteche mark). 1\n12350: Holland guilder). '.\u20196 32; Italy\nEi). -Id 1 Portugal (escudo*. 3.50; I\nlen (krona). 19 34: Switaerland\n(fee). 23.34; Denmark 1 krona 1.\nLatin America Argentina (free).\n7 SO. Brazil (free). 123; Mexico. 8.01;\nVenezuela (bolivar). M. 03.\nPar taat: Horn Kona dollar. 17 SO\nPrinciples.\" Specifically cited\nwere such claims as \"One Pen\nny Profit\u201d; \u201cJust Leave Us a\nBuck\"; \"Profit Is No Motive\";\n\"810 Ove