Rudolph J. Schaefer, the sons of\nMaximilian, and Edward C. and\nGeorgs G. Schaefer, sons of\nFrederick.\nAnd now we approach a gala\nevent in the history of the House\nof Schaefer\u2014the year 1892. The\nbusiness was fifty years old!\nSuitably in the style of the Gay\nNineties, the event was recorded\nin the painting which you see re\nproduced on the opposite page\u2014\nn memorable milestone marking\nthe first half century of service.\nThe artist depicts little gnomes\nmerrily brewing lager beer and j\namusingly pictures the alarm of/\nseveral of them as they view thtf\nsteam train puffing past thr\nbrewery on whst is now fashitV\nable Park Avenue.\nEverybody in thoee days v i\nFraaj; Lttlit't Illustrated WJ J\nOn June 15, 1893, under.\ntitle \u201cThe Virtues of Bees JB\npopular weekly festurw JfR\nF. AM. Schaefer Brewii/ Jf\nboth story and picture/ qf\nsurprise many to k vf\narticle states, \u201cthat tw\nof the tame firm\nlager beer in New\nliving, and that\nishing to a .r*-\"\never V*\"\npor yO'\nfifty\ncanes\n\u201cUn\\\narticles V'\nbeers w\u00ab\nof\nhasbe\u00ab\nall ove\\ WMSjI\nfrom anV\ncentury A\nOn Scp\\\ncontrol sni\nbusiness pA *4\nhands of rA\u2014. V\nSr., younger son of\nIt is interesting to note that in\nthat same year, his son, F. M. E.\nSchaefer, began his career with\nthe company nn event that\nmarks the entrance of the third\ngeneration upon the field of the\nfamily\u2019s activities. (P\nFour years later, prompted by\nincreasing land 1\nAvenue and the necessity ofj\u00df\npension, Rudolph J. SchdnsC 1\nSr., had tha foreal(ht to secure\nproperty on the Brooklyn water\nfront at South 9th Btreat and\nKant Avenue, where ha built a\nmw and modem brewery.\nNIW 7\nRecord Seen\nFor Finished\nSteel Output 1\nCLEVELAND. Oct. 21 UP).~\nConsumption of finished steel\nwill hit a record SI million tons\nthis year, with 84 million\ncoming from mill shipment*\nand the other million from In\nventories. Steel magaiine pre\ndicted yesterday. Last year\u2019s\nconsumption was about 79\nmillion tons.\nThe metalworking weekly\nsaid steel lnventorlsa totaled\naround 20 million tons at the\nbeginning of the year follow\ning a 4 million ton addition in\n1958. The net reduction of\na million tone in the lnven\n-1 torles will still leave 19 million\ntons in stock at the end of the\nyear, which Is equal to about\nthree months' usage, the mags\nzlne said.\nThe need to carry large In\nventories Is eliminated because\nmills are able to make prompt\ndelivery on all forms of steel\nexcept heavy plates and struc\ntural shapes, the publication\ni said. It added that aa long as\ninventory reduction is under;\n1 way there will be apathy In\nbuying.\nSteel said producers of\ncapital goods, such as machine\ntools and plant <equipmeul, are\ndisappointed about prospects\nfor new orders In the fourth\nquarter of 1957, but tl*ey see\nindications of an upturn in\n1958. probably In the thirdl\nquarter.\n\u201cMany consider the current\nslump as a breathing spell in\nwhich to consolidate their gains,\nof the last two abnormally high\nyears.\u201d the magazine said. i\ni Prices of steelmaking grades\nof scrap continued to fall.\nSteel's price composite dropped\n$1.67 to 137.83 a grots ton, the\nlowest point since July, 1955.\nThis youth of twenty-one lost\nno time in getting started. With\na eash capital of $1 00 he couldn't\nvery well afford to! And on No\nvember 5 we find him hard at\nwork in tha small New York\nbrewery of Sebastian Sommers.\nThings want well. On June\n6, 1840. Frederick Schaefer\u2019s\nyounger brother. Maximilian,\nsailed into busy New York har\nbor. Together the two young\nbrothers worked, planned\nand dreamed.\nLess than two years later their\nfondest dream came true. Despite\nthe grim outlook of Philip Hpfl'*\nformer mayor of NewY o>*omk\nfamous\nwrote. jiM\nconfidencejdg\nother\nvalue, tfjjpP MX Jj\nr(Hia. ei'JFjil\nM\nha.i JKHHn\ni |j|\nU.\u00ab.\neoV)***\nperiod that the*beer clsnhed *llB\u201c\ndeveloped its pUtsing taste and\nwholeaome mellowness. The re\nsult was a more palatable beer,\nlightwn body, which, unlike the\nitM Jeers of the time, poeaeeaed j\ncMvuTlding ninety hiuL cluoty.l\nTiRfSTEer, oF\n1845 the Schaefe^rother^^d\nIt neceasMpE\u00df\nary to larger quarters on Seventh\nAvenue, between 16th and 17th\nStreets. You see on this page tha\nTV SHOW I WilllSM Gorgon ia/THi\nj YOUR\nMONEY'S WORTH\nW SYLVIA FORTH\ni\n\nHHi\n\nWjESm l\nIs It Recession?\nAt a small, private meeting\nIn New York recently, William\nMeC. Martin. Federal Reserve\nBoard chairman, gave an off\nthe-record talk. Boon after the\nmeeting, rumors were swinging\naround Wall Street that Mr.\nMartin had said he thought\nthe economy was in for a bad\nslide, but that the Reserve\nBoard would do nothing to\ncushion It because we had to\ngo through these recessions now\nand then.\nThis rumor, said my excited\nand worried informants, was\na key reason the stock market\ntumbled so severely the week\nbefore last.\nWell, as is so often the case\nwith Wall Street rumors, this\none bore only a scant resem\nblance to the facte.\nWhat Mr. Martin did sdy,\naccording to a man I\u2019ve inter\nviewed who was at the meeting,\nwas that the Reserve Board was\nnot afraid we were In for a\nserious recession.\nWhat he did emphasize was\nthat the Central Bank was\ndedicated more than ever to\nslowing the economy's expan\nsion to a healthy pace that'\nwould be sustained without\ndevastating inflation.\nControl Is Aim\nWhat he pointed out was\nthat if we could keep booms\nunder control, we could keep\nbusts under control, too. and\nwhen declines came, they would\nInvolve only minor unemploy- j\nment and bearable losses in-!\nstead of towering joblessness\nand a general crash.\nAnd while he admitted the\nReserve Board's governors are\nacutely aware of the stock mar-,\nket's slump and they are \u201ccon-;\ncerned\u201d about its impact on\npsychology, they still are going l\nSMM* WWO *\u00abM wwnrs IKMMMMmHMMMmMMmmMMM\nThis light, mellow lager\ntinue'i to make friends, arid tV-'lz -~1\ndemand for S. haefer lieer\nt \u2019..nued to fop e tie two\nto expand the foewery\nth(y dt!. ,r f 3-'\nmall o j>e The /d6k v U s\ni\ni.-.,: ..r.423\nhist /Jlj\nr. \u2019r Bp\npermitted Hd of\nJQ| Kbki\nW\njmWJM Htusned \\V;:r\nwelitnd\nV*\u2019mh43r 5 *'k .-r. V-ij \u2022ti a:\nH.. ->rk ir. the srnah New York\n\u2022'\u25a0'WE \"Jt m\n-JM\nm ill\nll ,l l VVM*\u00ab w\neffort made to extend the buainees lai'Rllll n*\u00bbMia^\u2014.\nof this company to enormous consumed at room tempmiuu\nproportion ita natural growth fewEky* after fermentation was\nJBm been that it now extends corMleted.\n\u25a06l over Jew new lager beer, however,\nlEom an Ilsa wM made with a different type\nInjury BQIl# 1 which worked in low\nEpOir-S^MFi 1 tMiperaturse and settled to tht\njmtrol and management of the bmtom after completion of fer*\nHffhess passed Into tha able mentation. It also required a\nhands of Rudolph J. Schaefer, lengthy period of eecondary ter-\nSr., younger eon of Maximilian, mentation, during which the brew\nIt b interesting to note that in I was kept at rest in cold storage\u2014\nI NEW ADVENTURES OF MARGIN KANE\u201d! Tea* is Wednesday*\nalong on the assumption that\nthe stock market\u2019s retreat will\nnot Intensify the \"soft\u2019' spots\nIn business.\nYou have to hear it to believe\nIt\u2014you have to be in Wall\nBtreet on a day the stock mar\nket is cracking and listen to\nthe pessimism which results to\nrealize how emotional sup\nposedly hard-headed men can\nbe.\nI|>e very \"experts\u201d who In\nmid-summer were forecasting\ngreat business in the fall are\nnow arguing that the stock\nmarket's plunge In itself pre\ndicts that we\u2019re heading for a\nmajor recession.\nAre we?\nAccording to the Nation\u2019s eco\nnomic policy-makers\u2014who pre\nsumably have at their finger\ntips the most reliable informa\ntion available on business trends\n\u2014we are not\nThe zip Is out of the economy,\noptimism has given way to!\ncaution, business has flattened 1\nout.\nContradictory Trends\nThe economy has unmistak\ni ably moved onto a plateau and\nthe business picture Is now\ndotted with so many diverse\nand contradictory trends that,\neven the calmest observer must\nbe confused. For Instance\nBusiness spending for ex\npansion is leveling off and even\nturning down and that\u2019s a de\npressing force. But Govern\nment spending at all levels\u2014\nFederal. State and local\u2014ls ris\ning and that\u2019s a stimulant.\nCorporations are not building j\nup their Inventories and that\u2019s\na dampening factor. But con\nsumers are spending record\namounts and this spending Is a\nmighty prosperity prop.\nCorporation profits are drop\nping in many fields and that i\n\u25a0HKiv mi\nBANK SFEAKEB Dr.\nJohn K. Langum, well\nknown economist and\nformer viee president of\nthe Federal Reserve Bank\nof Chicago, will address\nthe fall economic meeting\nof the Union Trait Co.\nat Hotel Statler tomorrow\nafternoon.\nhas been a factor behind the\nselloff In stocks. But personal\nincomes are climbing and bil\nlions have been added to wages\nand salaries in 1957.\nBusinesses in many lines of\nj defense products are facing an\n.adjustment to a lower level of\nI sales and that prospect has\nchilled many areas. But such\nIndustries as housing are Im\nproving.\nIt\u2019s a contradictory economy,\nin short, in which some Indus\ntries are moving down while\nothers are moving up\u2014and the\nover-all pattern is one of activ\nity at a very high level.\nThis, in the Central Bank's\nview. U not recession. Rather,\nthis is an essential adjustment\nwhich will set the stage for the\nnext upswing as we progress\ntoward the new decade of\nthe \u20196os.\n(Dlstrlbutad 1957. bv the Hall\nSyndicate Inc. All rtfhts referred\nBlue-Blooded Clams\nBOSTON. Crabs, snails,\nclams and worm* all have blue\nblood.\n\u25a0\u25a0art o'com'\nto the light\nKs- heginn.ng\nBest.\"\nliiuLs\nH lager roit-\nBds. and the\n\u25a0r Beer